{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17649806","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17649806"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:07:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:07:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18380"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18380","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18380"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.74,0.22,0,0.04,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11098"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79549"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11098","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11098"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18380"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64853"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25732"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25736"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79549","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79549"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements is correct regarding ankle sprains?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inversion injuries account for the majority of ankle sprains","Eversion injuries are more common than inversion injuries","Clicks or snaps are the most reliable indicators of ankle sprains","The deltoid ligament is most commonly injured in ankle sprains","Ankle sprains rarely involve ligament damage"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAnkle sprains are a common type of musculoskeletal injury, often occurring during sports or physical activities. The mechanism of injury can vary, leading to different types of ligament damage. \u003Cstrong\u003EInversion injuries account for the majority of ankle sprains\u003C/strong\u003E. These injuries typically involve the lateral ligaments of the ankle, especially the anterior talofibular ligament.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEversion injuries are more common than inversion injuries\u003C/strong\u003E - Eversion injuries are less common due to the strength of the deltoid ligament\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClicks or snaps are the most reliable indicators of ankle sprains\u003C/strong\u003E - These sounds are not reliable indicators of the severity or presence of a sprain\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe deltoid ligament is most commonly injured in ankle sprains\u003C/strong\u003E - The deltoid ligament is strong and less commonly injured compared to lateral ligaments\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnkle sprains rarely involve ligament damage\u003C/strong\u003E - Ankle sprains typically involve damage to the ligaments\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Inversion injuries are the most common type of ankle sprain, accounting for approximately 85% of cases.","Eversion injuries are less common due to the strength of the deltoid ligament on the medial side of the ankle.","The lateral ligaments of the ankle, particularly the anterior talofibular ligament, are most commonly injured in inversion sprains."],"references":["Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Smith, R., \u0026 Wordsworth, P. (2016). Oxford textbook of clinical and biochemical disorders of the skeleton. Oxford University Press","Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2021). Textbook of Orthopaedics, 2e-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Dandy, D. J., \u0026 Edwards, D. J. (2009). Essential Orthopaedics and Trauma E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","MacGregor R, Byerly DW. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Foot Bones. 2023 May 23. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32491379"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64853"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18380"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64853","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64853"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-14T22:34:39+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-14T22:37:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11098"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79549"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"descri